[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'You have heard the take all over your feed. Stop using Docker. It is bloated, it is heavy, and some lighter tool is about to kill it. So, is it actually true? Today, we put that claim on trial. Here\'s what people are reacting to. A simple app wrapped in a Docker image can'

[00:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'balloon past a full gigabyte. An entire operating system shipped just to run a few kilobytes of your code, and it all runs through one process, the Docker daemon. A single program running as root that every command you type has to talk'

[00:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'to. One daemon to rule them all, and one daemon to fail. But, let me be honest with you right away. Docker is not dying. 67% of developers still reach for it first. The container itself is fine.'

[00:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'It is the heavy wrapper around it that people want gone. So, the real story is not stop using Docker. It is this. Docker is being unbundled. Two lighter tools are quietly pulling it apart, each'

[00:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'carrying away a different piece of the weight. Contender one is Podman, the same containers you already know, but with no daemon and no root. Built by Red Hat to be a true drop-in replacement, and it really is drop-in. You can'

[01:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'literally type alias docker equals podman, keep typing the exact same commands, and everything just works. Same images, same registries, same muscle memory. Contender two is stranger and more ambitious, WebAssembly. Instead'

[01:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'of shrinking the container, it throws the container out entirely and ships something far, far smaller. Look at the gap, that gigabyte Docker image against a WebAssembly module that can be just a'

[01:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'few megabytes, sometimes only kilobytes. 50 to 75 times smaller, and the speed. A container can take hundreds of milliseconds to cold start. A WebAssembly module starts in under one. That is not an optimization, that is a'

[01:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'whole different category. Let us slow down and look at each one properly. Podman first. Remember that single root daemon? Podman just deletes it. Every container runs as a normal child process of the command you ran. No middleman, no'

[01:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'single point of failure, and it is rootless by default. Your containers run as you, not as the all-powerful root user. Docker can do this, too, but in 2025, only about 8% of users had ever'

[02:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'switched it on. With Podman, you get it for free. Crucially, Podman speaks the same language, the same open container standard, the same image format, the same Dockerfiles. It pulls and runs your'

[02:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'existing Docker images with Docker not installed at all. The name is a hint. Podman thinks in pods, just like Kubernetes. You can group containers together, then have it generate real Kubernetes config straight from whatever'

[02:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'is running on your laptop. And dropping the daemon is not free for nothing. In tests, Podman started containers 20 to 50% faster, and running 50 containers at once, it used 15 to 20% less memory. So,'

[02:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'Podman is the easy switch. If you care about security, lockdown environments, or running containers in your build pipeline without a privileged daemon, it is a nearly painless upgrade.'

[02:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'WebAssembly is the bigger bet. It started in the browser, a way to run fast compiled code on a webpage. Take almost any language, Rust, Go, C, and compile it down to one tiny portable'

[03:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'binary. Then came WASI, the WebAssembly System Interface. It is the part that lets that binary out of the browser with controlled access to files, the network, and the clock. Suddenly, WASM can run'

[03:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'real server software. And the numbers are genuinely wild. A typical container image is 100 to 200 megabytes. The WASM equivalent is 2 to 5. Sitting idle, it sips under a megabyte of memory, where a'

[03:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'container wants 20 or more. That tiny size is why it starts so fast. Fermyon Spin can cold start a function in under half a millisecond. People call it the 5-millisecond cloud, fast enough to spin'

[03:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'up per request and scale all the way down to zero. It is also sandboxed by design. A Wasm module can do nothing, touch no file, open no socket, unless you explicitly hand it that exact'

[03:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'capability. Denied by default instead of a container that can quietly see the whole machine, and it is genuinely portable. One binary runs on any chip and any operating system. No more works on my machine. No more building separate'

[04:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'images for Intel and for ARM. Compile once, run anywhere for real this time. This is not just a research demo. Fermyon built Spin to deploy Wasm apps with no container layer at all. And in'

[04:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'December 2025, Akamai, one of the biggest edge networks on Earth, acquired them. Here is the twist that says it all. Docker itself now runs WebAssembly. One flag and the very same Docker command'

[04:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'launches a Wasm module instead of a container. Docker calls Wasm complementary, not a replacement. Now the honest part the hype video skip, that under 1 millisecond figure is the best case. Studies of real-world Wasm'

[04:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'apps measured cold starts from 300 milliseconds up to 2 and 1/2 seconds. The magic shrinks when the work gets real, and Wasm is still young. Full multi-threading and rich networking are'

[05:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'only now landing. The library ecosystem is thin. For a database, a message queue, or anything heavy on input and output, a container is still the right tool. So, it is not a fight to the death. Wasm wins for stateless edge'

[05:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'functions, tiny portable services, and security critical sandboxes. Containers win for stateful, heavy, messy, real-world systems. Different jobs, different tools, and underneath all of'

[05:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'it sits a quieter truth. The real engine actually running your containers is not Docker. It is containerd, now on version two. Even Kubernetes ripped Docker out of the loop years ago. Picture it as layers. At the bottom, a standard image'

[05:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'and a runtime like containerd. On top, an interchangeable face. Docker or Podman or Wasm. The face is what you are really choosing, not the engine, which is why most teams do not pick just one.'

[05:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'A very common pattern is Docker on the laptop, Podman in the build pipeline, and containerd in production. They mix the tools to fit each layer. So, stop using Docker? Not exactly. The accurate'

[06:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'version is less catchy. The big friendly monolith is being unbundled into lighter, sharper pieces, and you finally get to choose which one fits. Keep Docker for the developer experience and local work. Reach for Podman when you'

[06:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'need security and no daemon. Reach for WebAssembly when you need edge speed and scale to zero. The honest answer is, it depends. But the direction of travel is clear. Every one of these tools is'

[06:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'pulling the same way. Lighter, daemonless, rootless, and a smaller unit of compute. The heavy whale is being put on a diet. Here is my honest verdict. Docker taught an entire industry how to ship software, and that lesson is not'

[06:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'going anywhere. But the layer running underneath it is getting smaller, faster, and safer every single year. Four things to remember. Docker is not dying, it is being unbundled. Podman is'

[06:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'the drop-in, daemonless swap. WebAssembly is the smaller, faster unit. And containerd is the quiet engine under them all. So, do not stop using Docker. Start understanding what is actually'

[07:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'replacing it one piece at a time. If that was useful, you know what to do. I will see you in the next one.'
